|decision[seam-amortization-and-the-two-grid-overlay] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status superseded :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The topological charge can be AMORTIZED (physics) but not REMOVED (topology). Full reasoning — including the cube∪octahedron → cuboctahedron derivation and the rhombic-dodecahedral lead — is recorded in `ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md` §Addendum A1–A4, and MUST be incorporated into the pending grid-comparison report.
  |reason
    Joseph's intuition ("some way to do partial fluxes so that by the time you get to the worst area it's still 8 minus a little") is CORRECT. Conservation and routing do not depend on valence — flux is a boundary integral, and gradient-projected edge-flux routing (D-∞ on a mesh) fans outflow across however many edges exist as partial fluxes summing exactly. So the defect DEMOTES from a global conservation failure to a bounded local accuracy wart at 24 cells (LSQ gradients recover second order at any valence). **That is the argument that decides the grid does not need replacing.** The cube∪octahedron partition (Voronoi = cuboctahedron — Joseph guessed it before the derivation) is elegant and never evaluates a cell at a singularity, but it is an O(1)→O(N) trade and is recommended against — while its partial-edge MECHANISM is exactly right for the coarse↔fine tile seam, which is unavoidable and non-matching by nature.
  |ref ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md §Addendum · examples/grid_lab.rs · Snyder 1992 Table 1

|decision[conservation-is-not-consistency] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics :supersedes [seam-grid-leads-snyder-healpix snyder-closes-the-projection-lead]
  :note 2026-07-12 — DOWNGRADED decided -> proposed. The MEASUREMENTS below stand and reproduce. The VERDICT ("keep the grid, change the kernels") is NOT ratified — Joseph has not adjudicated it and the discussion is still to be had. Do not cite the grid question as closed. See `grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated`.
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  THE LEAD IS CLOSED, BY MEASUREMENT — and the earlier decision reached the RIGHT CONCLUSION FOR THE WRONG REASON. Keep the equiangular cube-sphere and CellId; change the KERNELS. But the load-bearing claim underneath that — "conservation is a SCHEME property, isotropy/shape is a GRID property no scheme fixes" — is FALSE, and correcting it changes what the kernel work actually is.
  |reason
    Nine grids measured on one harness (`examples/grid_lab/`, whole-sphere, combinatorial adjacency, Euler asserted): equiangular / Snyder-equal-area / gnomonic cube, rhombic dodecahedron ×2, HEALPix, icosahedral triangles, hexagonal Voronoi dual raw + SCVT. Snyder implemented from the PDF and REPRODUCES ITS OWN TABLE 1 for the cube (measured ω 25.17°, a 1.248, b 0.801). HEALPix from Górski §5.1/§5.3.
    **(1) Conservation is free and is not the question.** Finite volume conserves EXACTLY (~1e-15) on every grid, worst included — the flux across an edge is literally the same number added to one cell and subtracted from the other. No projection buys it; none is needed.
    **(2) But a TWO-POINT flux — the naive meaning of "FV with the true geometry" — is INCONSISTENT on a non-orthogonal mesh.** Its relative error is O(1) and GROWS under refinement (order **−0.5** on EVERY quad grid). The two-point difference measures ∇u along the CENTRE-LINE; the flux needs ∇u along the edge NORMAL, and the discarded tangential term scales as sinθ·R/h — and R/h doubles every time you refine. **So: conservation is a scheme property; CONSISTENCY is a property of the scheme AND the grid TOGETHER.** Exact conservation does not imply you are solving the right equation. The hexagonal duals are the control that proves it: exactly orthogonal by primal–dual duality (measured 0.00°), and there the SAME two-point scheme is already consistent (4e-4, order 1.7–1.9).
    **(3) The fix is scheme-side and it is bigger than "carry the metrics".** Correct the face gradient (project both centres onto the edge normal THROUGH THE MID-EDGE — the arm earns its keep here — and extrapolate; antisymmetric under i↔j so conservation stays exact) AND widen the gradient stencil (QUADRATIC fit over the 8 Moore neighbours; a linear fit over the 4 edge-neighbours is only first-order and caps the whole scheme at ~0.5 order). Our own grid: **9.2e-1 → 3.6e-4, a 2500× gain, order −0.50 → +1.63**, against the best hexagonal mesh's 2.2e-4. Same order of magnitude, on the metric hexagons exist to win — with NO change to CellId, the quadtree, the store, Hilbert locality, or the KRNG.
    **(4) Equal-area buys ONE metric and it is not the one that matters.** Only `cell_area` hoists (Snyder, HEALPix); edge length, arm and distance stay variable on every grid here. And equal-area's real cost is SHAPE: HEALPix has the WORST non-orthogonality (36.7°) and skew (49.6%) in the report and comes LAST among the quad grids on accuracy. Also newly measured and not in the literature we read: **equal-area is a property of the continuous MAP that the discrete cell does not inherit** — Snyder's and HEALPix's cell boundaries are not great circles, so the geodesic polygon an FV code actually builds is 4.96% / 9.96% off the equal-area cell. You can have exactly-equal AREAS or great-circle EDGES, not both.
    **(5) The corner anisotropy figure is superseded.** "1.16–1.25×, does not converge away" was a two-point scheme on a single OPEN face. Whole-sphere with correct cross-face adjacency: **1.0025**, and **1.0000** under the corrected scheme.
  |impact
    Full report: `ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md` (table-driven, every number sourced M/P/D/I, structured so a reader with different algorithms reads off THEIR metric). Work, in the LADDER's order (not physics order — `check-the-ladder-not-modern-earth` applies): the erosion routing fix is gated behind `emerged-land` and is NOT on the critical path; **`water.rs` is live now and benefits immediately**. (1) corrected face gradient + WIDE stencil; (2) metric planes per (face, level); (3) erosion's routing, when the ladder licenses it; (4) tile seam = Berger–Colella flux register — and the corrected seam number (2.45/3.76/5.79, growing with the age gap while the interior stays flat) is exactly the signature of mean-pin conserving block MEANS but not boundary GRADIENTS, i.e. case (i) without case (ii).
    **BIGGEST OPEN RISK, unprobed: the corrected scheme's hot-loop cost.** A 5×5 solve per cell per step. Nobody has benchmarked it, including me. It plausibly wants a per-(face,level) precomputed stencil matrix (the geometry is static) — but that is an INFERENCE, not a result, and it should be measured before item (1) is committed to.
  |ref ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md · crates/vivarium-world/examples/grid_lab/ · Snyder 1992 Cartographica 29(1) Table 1 · Górski et al. 2005 §5.1/§5.3 · ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md §Addendum A1–A4

|decision[corner-pathology-confirmed-but-mfd-does-close] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic physics :supersedes corner-pathology-is-a-diagonal-artifact
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  PROVEN, WITH ONE CLAUSE FALSIFIED. The valence-3 corner IS an artifact of MFD's 8-neighbour fan, and gradient-projected edge flux does dissolve it. But the proposal asked us to "show edge-flux routing closes at valence 3 WHERE 8-NEIGHBOUR MFD CANNOT" — and **that second clause is false. MFD closes there perfectly well.**
  |reason
    Built the real whole-sphere corner topology (three faces meeting; combinatorial cross-face adjacency; Euler asserted). Measured, 6·32² cells: **every cell has exactly 4 EDGES, the 24 corner cells included** — the defect exists ONLY in the diagonal (Moore) stencil, which has 7 there instead of 8. Then ran three routers on a perfect cone (radially symmetric, and it has an EXACT answer: specific catchment area = R·tan(θ/2), Tarboton's test) — **all three conserve to 1.000000000000, MFD included.** A normalised-weight router conserves on ANY graph: the weights sum to one whether there are 8 neighbours or 7 or 3. **The corner was never a conservation bug.** This is Addendum A1 confirmed by measurement (conservation does not depend on valence; flux is a boundary integral).
    What the corner ACTUALLY breaks is (a) the CODE's structural assumption of eight fixed (dx,dy) offsets — which indexes a cell that does not exist — and (b) the fan's DIRECTIONAL weighting: the surviving 7 neighbours are not 45° apart and are not at cell_m·√2. And the routers separate on ACCURACY over the WHOLE grid, not at the corners: 8-nbr Moore MFD **20.76%** mean error vs gradient-projected edge flux **5.17%** (and 60.59% vs 19.67% AT the defects). **Grid-aligned bias is a face-wide defect of the fan, not a corner defect. The corner is a red herring; the fan is the bug.**
    Accuracy at the defect under the corrected scheme: converges at order **0.91** vs **1.55** in the far field — degraded, still converging, never leaking. **The defect is DEMOTED to a bounded local accuracy wart at 24 cells, exactly as A1 argued.**
    TRAP FOUND IN THE DOING: a gradient-projected router MUST be clamped to strictly-downhill edges. The LSQ gradient is a fit, so its outgoing component through an edge can be positive even when that neighbour is HIGHER; route there and the mass goes upstream past an elevation-ordered sweep and is never recovered. Measured before the guard: conservation **0.000** instead of 1.000. One line, and nothing in the scheme's DESIGN tells you it is needed.
  |impact
    Erosion's routing becomes gradient-projected edge flux (D-∞ on a mesh): no diagonals, any valence, exact conservation, 4× more accurate, and the 24-cell special case evaporates. **But per `check-the-ladder-not-modern-earth`, `charge[erosion-carving]` is a Phase-3 gate and there is nothing to carve until `emerged-land` is kept — so this is correct work, not urgent work.** `water.rs` needs no corner special case at all (verified primary: fl/fr/ft/fb ARE per-edge fluxes kept between steps, 4-neighbour). **NEW, and not previously flagged:** water also runs a θ flux-smoothing pass (de Almeida et al. 2012) that reads NEIGHBOURING FLUXES (`water.rs:362–370`) — a SECOND stencil, on the flux field, that will need its own halo and its own seam treatment. "Water is already flux-form" does not cover it.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/examples/grid_lab/flow.rs · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md §6 · water.rs:211,362–370 · erosion.rs NEIGHBORS/accumulate_drainage

|decision[configuration-classes-are-two-not-ten] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  CORRECTION to a number in `geometric-contract-metric-set`, not to its structure. The DISCRETE/CONTINUOUS split is exactly right and is the answer. But the "~10" is attached to the wrong half: the discrete class count is **2**, and the ~10 is the GEOMETRIC count, which does NOT stay finite.
  |reason
    Measured by level on our own grid. **Topological classes (valence, Moore-count): 2 — at EVERY level** (a regular cell, and a defective one; the defective set is a fixed 24 cells world-wide, forever). **Geometric/congruence classes at 1%: L1→1, L2→3, L3→10, L4→36, L5→134, L6→509.** Joseph's "~10 at the coarsest level" is EXACT at L3 — and it is a coincidence of that level, not a law: the count grows as **N²/8** (the face's D₄ symmetry folds an N×N face into an N²/8 fundamental domain).
    Reading "~10" as "the discrete branch has about ten arms" would build a fixed dispatch table that is correct at L3 and wrong at L4. The correct reading is the one the decision's own structure already implies: **branch on the discrete class (2 arms, a cheap branch), and COMPUTE the continuous metrics — do not tabulate them.** They can be computed, because they are analytic in position and identical for every tile on a face at a given level. That is Putman & Lin §3 verbatim ("cell areas, grid lengths, and a non-orthogonal metric factor ... are DERIVED QUANTITIES").
  |impact
    The nomos-declares-what-it-needs / grid-declares-what-it-provides / audit-matches design is unaffected and still right. Only the sizing changes: the branch is smaller than hoped (2, not 10) and the metric table is not a table at all (it is a function, or a few f32 planes per (face, level)).
  |ref ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md §4.6 · crates/vivarium-world/examples/grid_lab/probes.rs (classes)

|decision[grid-report-supersedes-two-of-my-claims] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
