|decision[algorithms-are-disguised-physical-claims] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  AN ALGORITHM'S COORDINATE ASSUMPTIONS ARE A DISGUISED PHYSICAL CLAIM, AND THAT CLAIM IS WHAT WE PORT — NOT THE ALGORITHM. When a published algorithm's assumptions do not survive our sphere or our multi-scale demands, the move is NOT to bend the grid to it, patch its parameters, or wave the violation through. The move is to recover the PHYSICS the algorithm was always asserting, and build the algorithm that actually does that on our topology. Joseph has been advocating this from the beginning; it is the standing frame for every nomos.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "if we can't get the existing algorithm to realistically line up with a sphere or our need for multi-scale — we learn what the algorithm's underlying *physics* are and we build the better algorithm that does what we need it to do." And on why the prior approach failed him: "It has been far too easy to just do what the paper said it was doing, plus some alterations to get it to work 'in our system.' That's never what I've wanted."
    WORKED EXAMPLE (the one that made it concrete). `erosion.rs` routes drainage with **MFD** (Multiple Flow Direction): split outflow among the 8 Moore neighbours, slope-weighted. Its coordinate assumption is "8 neighbours, 45 deg apart, diagonals at cell*sqrt(2)". Its PHYSICAL claim is "distribute outflow over the downhill directions in proportion to slope" — MFD is a QUADRATURE, and those 8 cells are its quadrature NODES. On our cube-sphere the nodes are NOT evenly spaced, so the quadrature is biased — which attacks MFD exactly where it lives, since killing D8's grid-aligned-river bias is MFD's entire reason to exist. And four of those eight "neighbours" share only a VERTEX with the cell: a zero-length edge, across which NO FLUX PHYSICALLY CROSSES. The diagonals were never physics; they were a hack against grid bias. Recovering the physical claim gives the honest algorithm directly: take the flow DIRECTION from the reconstructed gradient (a continuous angle, D-inf's idea) and split outflow across the cell's REAL EDGES — of which there are exactly 4 at every cell on the sphere, the 24 "defective" corner cells included. No fan, no diagonals, no fixed-distance assumption, any valence, exactly conservative. Measured 5.17% vs MFD-8's 20.76% error against a cone's exact answer.
    ⚠ AND IT EXPLAINS WHY THE CORNER OBSESSION WAS A DEAD END. Months went into the valence-3 corner because people audited the COORDINATE structure ("the diagonal cell doesn't exist!") instead of the algorithm's PHYSICAL assumption ("even angular sampling") — which our grid was already violating at ordinary interior cells, in plain sight. The corner was never the problem; the fan was. This frame catches that on the first pass. The valence frame never would have.
  |impact
    Standing frame for every nomos. Practically: (1) each nomos should DECLARE the physical assumption its coordinate shorthand stands for (this is the geometric contract, and it belongs beside `consumes`/`produces`); (2) the grid declares what it actually delivers; (3) the audit reports the GAP — and, crucially, **whether that gap is a BIAS or is NOISE** (see `bias-vs-noise-is-the-decisive-audit`). This is `physics-not-knobs` applied to GEOMETRY rather than to constants.
  |ref erosion.rs (NEIGHBORS / accumulate_drainage) · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md SS6 · doc/plan/regula-conformance-design.md

|decision[bias-vs-noise-is-the-decisive-audit] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  WHEN A DISCRETIZATION IS WRONG, THE MAGNITUDE OF THE ERROR IS THE SECOND QUESTION. THE FIRST IS: IS IT A BIAS, OR IS IT NOISE? A 20% *unbiased* error largely washes out — drainage area sums over a large upstream catchment and the law of large numbers eats it. A 20% *directionally-biased* error MANUFACTURES A FAKE PHYSICAL LAW (rivers preferring grid axes) and COMPOUNDS down the catchment. Same magnitude; categorically different harm. This distinction is currently NOWHERE in the framework, and it should be a declared field of the geometric contract.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12, reaching for it: an error is tolerable if it "doesn't accumulate until it hits some place where it causes actual physical dishonesty." That is precisely the bias/noise carve. Its consequences are immediate and they REORDER the options available when an algorithm's assumption fails on our topology:
    • "the error is negligible at this scale" is admissible ONLY if the error is NOISE. If it is BIAS, that defence is never admissible at any scale — a fake law does not become true when you zoom in.
    • FATED STOCHASTIC JITTER (Joseph's proposal) is thereby not a hack but a principled move: it is a BIAS -> VARIANCE conversion, exactly right when bias is the harm and variance washes out. It is dithering, it stays deterministic (fated noise), and normalization keeps it conservative. It is STRICTLY WEAKER than recovering the physics (it makes the error honest without making it small), but it is a legitimate FALLBACK if the principled kernel proves unaffordable in the hot loop.
    • JENSEN'S INEQUALITY MAKES THIS UNAVOIDABLE AT EVERY SEAM (see `column-is-a-control-volume-with-sufficient-statistics`): coarse-graining a NONLINEAR law is a BIAS, not a loss of precision.
  |impact
    Add bias-vs-noise to the geometric contract as a declared, audited field. A probe is running (2026-07-12) to measure whether MFD's routing error on our grid is directional bias or noise — that number decides whether the erosion routing rewrite is urgent or merely correct.

|decision[flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  PROPOSAL: make the FLUX a first-class, keyed, STORED object living ON THE FACE (a staggered store), instead of a transient computed-and-discarded quantity. **Then refluxing stops being an ALGORITHM and becomes an INVARIANT: the coarse face's flux IS the sum of its children's fluxes — not by correction, but by construction, because they are the same object at two resolutions.**
  |reason
    **This was Joseph's mental model from the beginning, and it was misheard — twice.** He wrote (2026-07-12, in his own grid objectives): *"distance from midpoint to vertices and from midpoint to edge-centers — **or rather to the edge-centers of the adjacent shapes along that edge for multiple smaller scales on any given side**."* We read that as a **METRIC** (the centre-to-mid-edge arm — a length to compute, which it also is, and which the grid report duly measured). **He meant it as an ONTOLOGY: the edge-centre is WHERE A FLUX LIVES.** That is the entire difference between "carry the metrics" and "stagger the grid," and we spent months on the former.
    **And his second clause is the harder half — the one the textbook staggered picture does NOT have.** A standard Arakawa C-grid assumes MATCHED faces (one flux per face, neighbour of equal size). Joseph's phrasing — *"the edge-centers of the adjacent shapes… for multiple smaller scales"* — says a coarse cell's face is **SUBDIVIDED by its finer neighbour into several sub-faces, each carrying its own flux**, and the coarse flux must equal **the sum of its children's**. **That is a mortar interface. That is a Berger–Colella flux register. He described REFLUXING, structurally, before anyone told him it was missing.**
    **WHY OUR REFLUXING IS HARD, DIAGNOSED:** what got built is **cell-centred, collocated, mean-pinned tiles** — a design in which **there are no face objects at all**. A flux is computed, used, and thrown away; it has no identity, no key, no home in the store. **So when the coarse tile and the fine tile disagree about what crossed their shared boundary, THERE IS NOTHING TO RECONCILE WITH — the evidence was discarded.** Refluxing must then reconstruct it after the fact, which is exactly why it is hard and exactly why it is still unbuilt.
    **AND IT SNAPS ONTO THE WAVELET STORE WITH NO SEAM** (`preserve-the-structure-declare-the-sacrifice` §3.7): the coarse face flux is the **low-pass** of the fine face fluxes, and the *disagreement* — the very thing a flux register stores — **IS the detail coefficient**. Same object, two lenses, one design.
  |impact
    Design consequence, concretely: **the store keys CELLS today; a staggered store must key FACES too** — and a face is shared between two cells, possibly at DIFFERENT levels. So face identity needs its own addressing discipline (standard move: each face owned by exactly one of its two cells, canonically the lower `CellId`, stored once and read twice). That is a real, tractable change to `store.rs` / `query.rs`, and **it is the thing that makes the seam an identity instead of a repair.** Weigh together with: the staggering lead (`TODO` §grid), the wavelet-store spike, and the column-semantics fork — they are one design, not four. **NOT DECIDED — this is Claude's proposal on Joseph's model; the grid/scheme question remains open and is his.**
  |ref doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS7 + fig/staggering.svg · TODO.md SS discretisation-foundation · crates/vivarium-world/src/{store,query}.rs

|decision[mean-pin-does-not-preserve-block-means] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ MEASURED, AND IT FALSIFIES A LAW OF THE OPERATOR ALGEBRA. **`erosion.rs::pin_block_means` does NOT preserve block means.** It is not `h <- mean(h)`; it is `h <- h + BilinearUpsample(target - BlockMean(h))` — a SMOOTHED DELTA INJECTION. Bilinear upsampling of a block-wise field does not preserve block means; its block mean is exactly the **(1,6,1)/8 stencil**, so the residual is **(Δb²/8)·∇²(delta)**. ⇒ **`ARCHITECTURE.md` law (1) — "mean-pinning a fine erosion tier to its parent is R∘L = id ON THE MEAN, live" — is FALSE as implemented.** Same false claim in `doc/theory/multiscale-methods.md` §1 and `multiscale-seams.md` §2.1. **All three corrected 2026-07-13.**
  |reason
    Measured against the real kernel (96×96 L19, verified-land footprint, B=4): mean |block mean − target| = **0.43 m, max 2.97 m** at 30 epochs, and the predicted (1,6,1)/8 ⊗ (1,6,1)/8 residual matches to **1.1e-4 m** — mechanism IDENTIFIED, not merely observed. **And it GROWS with the age gap:** 0.20 m (6 epochs) → 0.43 (30) → 0.85 (60) → **1.93 m mean / 7.96 m max (150)**. **corr(residual, ∇² of the eroded coarse surface) = −0.42** — the error tracks the very ridges and valleys erosion is manufacturing.
    ⚠ **AND THE GUARD WAS WRITTEN TO PASS.** The in-tree test is *named* `pin_preserves_parent_means`, carries a **2.0 m tolerance**, and its own comment admits the mechanism: *"Bilinear upsampling smooths deltas, so means match approximately."* **A test named for an invariant it does not test, with a tolerance sized to accommodate the defect.** This is the same species as the DESIGN-MATERIAL §4 guard that a later tier drifted straight through: **a declaration that cannot fail a build is a wish.**
    **[inferred] A SECOND, UNNAMED CANDIDATE FOR THE SEAM RIDGE.** The age signature matches `seam_ridge` (2.45× / 3.76× / 5.79×, growing with the differential age gap while the interior stays flat). The documented cause is *"mean-pin conserves block means but not boundary gradients."* **It does not conserve block means either.** NOT claiming this IS the cause — claiming there are now TWO candidates where the project believed there was one, and they are separable by experiment.
  |impact
    **CHEAP, DECISIVE, AND IT CAN FAIL — run it first:** replace the bilinear delta upsample with a **block-constant** delta injection (which preserves the block mean EXACTLY and costs less), then **re-run `seam_ridge`. If the ridge drops, mechanism 2 was real.** Also: fix the guard to test the invariant it is named for, or rename it honestly.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs:498 (pin_block_means) + test pin_preserves_parent_means · doc/ARCHITECTURE.md law (1) · doc/theory/{multiscale-methods.md SS1, multiscale-seams.md SS2.1} · examples/seam_ridge.rs

|decision[theta-is-lax-friedrichs-not-rhie-chow] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ RETRACTION OF MY OWN CLAIM. I asserted that `water.rs`'s θ flux-smoothing is **Rhie–Chow-class stabilisation** curing an **invisible (checkerboard/null) mode** — the "travelling soliton blobs." **BOTH HALVES ARE FALSIFIED.** (1) **Wrong family:** de Almeida et al. 2012 say their momentum discretisation is *"inspired by the **Lax-Friedrichs** model"* — a monotone-flux / artificial-viscosity device from the HYPERBOLIC-conservation-law lineage. **Rhie–Chow cures a rank deficiency of a COLLOCATED grid — and `water.rs` is ALREADY STAGGERED** (its head operator is `η_i − η_j` ACROSS the face: a 2-point difference at spacing Δ, symbol `2·sin(kΔ/2)/Δ`, which at Nyquist is `2/Δ ≠ 0`). **There is no null mode for a Rhie–Chow term to cure.** (2) **Measured:** feed the real kernel its own Nyquist mode and it **decays to 78% in 8 steps** — damped by the head operator alone, with θ provably a no-op on step 1 (the flux arrays start at zero). **A null mode is invariant or grows without resistance. Ours is SEEN and DAMPED.**
  |reason
    ⚠ **AND `water.rs` IS A COUNTEREXAMPLE TO MY OWN SS7(a)**, which claimed staggering ⇒ *"no stabilisation needed… never required."* **`water.rs` IS staggered, HAS no null mode, and needs THREE stabilisers.** SS7(a) and SS2.5 cannot both be right, and SS2.5's diagnosis is the wrong one.
    **[inferred — the replacement hypothesis, and it is testable] THE SOLITONS ARE PROBABLY ROLL WAVES, WHICH ARE PHYSICALLY REAL.** Travelling multi-metre waves with near-dry troughs is the signature of the **Vedernikov instability**, not a stationary checkerboard. Standard relation `Ve = (β−1)·Fr`, unstable at `Ve > 1`: Chézy (β=3/2) → **Fr = 2**; **Manning (β=5/3 — what `water.rs` uses) → Fr = 1.5**. ⚠ **`water.rs` counts supercritical cells at `Fr > 1.5` and caps breaking flux at `Fr = 2.0`. Those are exactly the Manning and Chézy roll-wave criticals.** No claim about intent — but the numbers line up with a **physical** instability, not a numerical one.
    ⇒ **If so, θ is not suppressing a numerical artifact; it is suppressing a REAL PHENOMENON the scheme cannot render** — because local-inertial drops the very advection term that sets a roll wave's shape and speed. **And Joseph's 2026-07-02 judgment — *"waves with dry ground between them are physically absurd"* — is then the thing to revisit: THAT IS WHAT ROLL WAVES LOOK LIKE.** ⚠ This is a hypothesis with a probe attached, NOT a finding, and it touches a call Joseph made himself. **THE PROBE THAT DECIDES IT:** raise Manning `n` until `Ve < 1` at fixed θ. *Blobs vanish with friction alone ⇒ roll waves (physical). Only θ kills them ⇒ numerical mode.*
    **SURVIVES:** *"θ's physical claim is NONE."* The primary agrees in the authors' own words — θ is *"a weighting factor that adjusts the amount of **artificial numerical diffusion**"*, coefficient `(1 − θ)`. ⚠ **But `water.rs:352` says otherwise and nobody reconciled them:** it calls θ *"the stand-in for the neglected momentum-advection term"* — **a physical claim, un-sourced, that the cited paper does not make.**
    **SURVIVES, DIFFERENT MECHANISM: θ IS a bias.** Not unpaired dissipation — **[D]** θ **preserves the flux mean and destroys flux VARIANCE** (**[M]** 24% over 200 passes). Sediment capacity ∝|v| and incision ∝ vⁿ are **superlinear** ⇒ **by Jensen, this systematically UNDER-predicts transport.**
  |impact
    Retract the Rhie–Chow identification from `doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md` SS2.5 and SS7(a) (done 2026-07-13). Reconcile or delete `water.rs:352`'s un-sourced physical claim. Run the roll-wave probe before touching θ. **The null-space probe remains right and remains worth running — but as the GRID-GENERAL instrument (rank deficiency is a linear-algebra statement; the Fourier/Nyquist version is the uniform-lattice special case), not as a prosecution of θ.**
  |ref de Almeida et al. 2012 WRR 48 W05528 · de Almeida & Bates 2013 WRR 49:4833 · crates/vivarium-world/src/water.rs:352,362-370 · doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS2.5

|decision[water-runs-outside-its-published-validity-envelope] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ THE BIGGEST FINDING IN THE WATER AUDIT, AND IT IS NOT THE ONE I WENT LOOKING FOR. **de Almeida & Bates 2013 — the applicability study `water.rs` ITSELF CITES — bounds the local-inertial approximation at Fr < 0.5 (near-identical to full SWE), diverging to Fr = 1, and states outright that *"the physical characteristics of the flow field of supercritical flow with a Froude number of greater than 1 CANNOT BE CORRECTLY EXPRESSED by the local inertial model."*** **MEASURED on real 60-epoch eroded land (2 m sheet, 400 steps of the real kernel): ~5.7% of wet cells run SUPERCRITICAL (Fr > 1.5)** — and those are the steepest, fastest cells, i.e. **exactly the ones doing the erosive work.**
  |reason
    ⚠ **AND THE INSTRUMENT IS READING ITS OWN CLAMP.** `max Fr = 2.00`, **bit-identical at every sample**. The breaking cap is **SATURATED**. That is the same species of tell as the "22888" divide-by-zero (`seam-probes-were-measuring-seabed`): *a bit-identical number across independent samples is not a physical measurement.* We have been reporting a clamp as a Froude number.
    ⇒ **The honest audit finding is not "θ lacks a fluctuation partner." It is: WE ARE RUNNING OUTSIDE THE PUBLISHED VALIDITY ENVELOPE OF THE MOMENTUM EQUATION WE CHOSE, AND THREE STABILISERS ARE HOLDING IT TOGETHER.**
    **AND THE PRIMARY NAMES THE BIAS IN SIGNED TERMS:** the local-inertial approximation *"leads to **milder water depth gradients** … attenuated spatial changes in depth"* and *"**slower flood propagation speeds**."* That is a **bias**, from **dropping advection** — not from unpaired dissipation.
    ⚠ **THREE ONE-SIDED CLIPS I NEVER MENTIONED, each a BIAS BY CONSTRUCTION under our own `bias-vs-noise-is-the-decisive-audit`** (a sign-definite operation CANNOT average out) — while θ, the term I prosecuted, is the **symmetric** one: `(f + dt*g*hflow*head).max(0.0)` · the Froude cap `f.min(2.0*(g*hflow).sqrt()*hflow*l)` (**measured saturated**) · `if out > depth*area { scale down }`. Also `depth = (…).max(0.0)` — **a positivity clamp is a silent MASS SOURCE if it fires. Unprobed.**
    ⚠ **AND WE CANNOT TEST ANY OF IT AS WRITTEN.** θ (`0.8`), the Froude cap (`2.0`), and Jarrett's `1.6`/`0.13` are **HARDCODED LITERALS inside `WaterSim::step()`** — not `WaterParams` fields. **An assumption you cannot vary is an assumption you cannot test.** This structurally blocks the probes. *(Also flagged: `water.rs:357` runs an IN-PLACE Gauss–Seidel θ sweep where de Almeida specify a JACOBI average — measured not mirror-symmetric (1.9e-3), ~1% more variance removed. An undeclared deviation from the cited paper: an ASSUMPTIONS line, not a rewrite.)*
  |impact
    **ORDER OF WORK.** (1) **Promote the hardcoded literals to `WaterParams` fields** — NOTHING below can run until this lands. (2) **Count the clip activation rates** — the audit needs those, not θ's. (3) **Run the roll-wave probe** (`theta-is-lax-friedrichs-not-rhie-chow`). (4) **`ASSUMPTIONS.md`'s "used as intended" for the de Almeida terms is the claim to RETIRE** — the primary's intent is bounded at Fr < 0.5–1.0, and we run 5.7% of the wet domain above Fr 1.5 with the cap saturated. This is an ASSUMPTIONS row, and it is currently unfalsifiable.
  |ref de Almeida & Bates 2013 WRR 49:4833 (the applicability study water.rs cites) · crates/vivarium-world/src/water.rs · ASSUMPTIONS.md (de Almeida row)

|decision[wavelet-store-solves-the-representation-not-the-dynamics] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture :supersedes flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ RETRACTION. My claim that a multiresolution/wavelet store *"makes the coarse↔fine seam an IDENTITY"* and *"may retire `detail→abstract`"* **DIES — and it dies against my own document.** SS3.3 proves coarse-graining does NOT commute with a nonlinear law (Jensen). SS3.7 then claims the seam becomes an identity. **Both are in the same document and they contradict each other. THE SEAM *IS* THE NON-COMMUTATION SS3.3 PROVES.**
  |reason
    **The honest restatement:** *a multiresolution store makes the coarse↔fine **REPRESENTATION** an exactly invertible identity. It does NOT make the **DYNAMICS** commute, and it cannot — that is Jensen.* I conflated a statement about the representation with a statement about the dynamics.
    **(a) "Refluxing is necessary because mean-pin discarded the information" — FALSE, and OUR OWN DOC SAYS SO.** `multiscale-seams.md` SS2.1, primary-read from Berger–Oliger: *"**Refluxing** … is **distinct from injection** … (Mean-pin ≈ injection, **not** refluxing.)"* Refluxing corrects a **flux mismatch between two independently-run solvers**. The fine fluxes are **computed and available — not discarded**. Storing state *details* gives you neither: **flux is a nonlinear function of state AND the scheme.**
    **(b) "May retire `detail→abstract`" — I INVERTED THE PROBLEM STATEMENT.** `multiscale-seams.md` SS2.4 opens: *"Forward/downward (L, and **dynamics-upscaling R for continuous fields**) is **MATURE**… What is unsolved anywhere is upward R of an **IRREDUCIBLE DISCRETE EDIT** … **not a statistical closure** … and the up-propagation must **invalidate cached macro derivations**."* I wrote that state upscaling is *"what ORIENTATION's open problem is about."* **It is not — state upscaling is the MATURE half. The "residue" I waved off IS the problem**, and it is the same nonlinearity SS3.3 proves.
    **(c) SUPERSEDES `flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant` — SAME CATEGORY ERROR, with an unwritten bill.** "The coarse face's flux IS the sum of its children's" is an identity **only if you DEFINE it so** — which means **the coarse tier can no longer be evaluated without running the fine tier.** That destroys the coarse tier's INDEPENDENCE, which is the entire point of the memoized store. **Berger–Colella pay this as an explicit correction; calling it "an invariant" hides the bill.**
    **WHAT SURVIVES, AND IS STILL WORTH BUILDING:** `fine = coarse ⊕ detail` is an exactly invertible **representation**; the coarse coefficient IS a linear functional of the fine ones; a **state** delta propagates to the root in **O(log N) exactly**; refinement-by-detail-magnitude is right; the store compresses. ⚠ On non-uniform areas it is a **lifted / second-generation wavelet** (Sweldens), **not Haar** — a correction to the LABEL, not the structure. *(And the "Haar assumes equal weights" objection I raised against myself **fails at the scale that matters**: the 1.4× area spread is a WHOLE-FACE figure; WITHIN a parent block it collapses to 1.006× at L5 and **1.000008× at L19** — measured worst-case 8.5e-6 m on 143 m of relief. Harmless where we run.)*
    ⚠ **AND JITTER FIGHTS JENSEN — a consequence I did not draw.** Jitter is a bias→variance conversion, and variance washes out **under summation**. **Drainage area is a SUM — linear — so it does.** But **stream power K·A^m·S^n is SUPERLINEAR in S: injecting variance into S and applying a convex function MANUFACTURES A NEW JENSEN BIAS.** Measure that before adopting jitter as the fallback.
  |impact
    The wavelet-store spike (in flight) should be re-scoped: **build the representation, and do NOT claim the dynamics.** Correct SS3.7 and the flux-on-face entry. **`detail→abstract` remains OPEN and remains the hard problem; nothing here touches it.**
  |ref doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS3.3, SS3.7 · doc/theory/multiscale-seams.md SS2.1, SS2.4 · crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs (pin_block_means)

|decision[preserve-the-structure-declare-the-sacrifice] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  :note 2026-07-13 — AUTHORITY SELF-CORRECTED (was `:by us :status decided`), caught by the onboarding audit. **Joseph never ratified THIS principle.** He ratified the COLUMN framing ("it very much lands" — see `column-is-a-control-volume-...`'s :status-note), and this entry's own |reason quotes him about JITTER, not about the principle. **The instance that wrote the authority legend on 07-12 tagged its own governing principle `:by us` on 07-13 and put it into CLAUDE.md the same day** — which is the exact failure the legend exists to prevent, committed by its author, one day later. The PRINCIPLE stands on its merits and is still Level-A reading; only the TAG was false. Joseph may promote it to `:by us :status decided` with a :status-note, or veto it.
  THE GOVERNING PRINCIPLE FOR EVERY FIELD NOMOS. **Identify the STRUCTURE the physics has — conservation laws, potentials, topological identities, symmetries, the second law, realizability, the timescale hierarchy — and choose a discretisation that preserves THAT structure EXACTLY. Everything else is negotiable and must be DECLARED as sacrificed. No scheme preserves all of them; you are ALWAYS choosing, and the sin is choosing silently.** Full treatment, with the taxonomy, the structure table, and the probes: `doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md` (Level-B required reading before authoring or reworking a field nomos).
  |reason
    Out of Cardiff & Demirdzic's FV review (read directly; Joseph supplied it) plus the information-theoretic reading Joseph asked for. **"Conserve mass" is a SPECIAL CASE, not the principle** — FVM is simply the scheme that chose LOCAL CONSERVATION as its exactly-preserved structure. It is right for mass/sediment/water and **WRONG for orbits (symplectic), rotating flow (vorticity), and shocks (entropy)** — and an agent who reaches for it there will build a world that **conserves beautifully and lies**. Two traps the structure table makes explicit: **conservation is NECESSARY BUT NOT SUFFICIENT** (a perfectly conservative scheme can converge to a non-physical weak solution — an expansion shock conserves mass and momentum and RUNS TIME BACKWARDS); and **positivity and well-balancedness are NOT conservation laws** — conservation says *the books balance*, realizability says *this state can exist at all*, and a scheme can honour one while destroying the other (negative water depth makes c=sqrt(gh) imaginary: the PDE CHANGES TYPE).
    **THE INFORMATION-THEORETIC RESTATEMENT, which subsumes it and which Joseph found far more native:** a discretisation is a **LOSSY COMPRESSION** of a field. Conservation = it preserves certain integrals exactly. Consistency = it preserves the operator. **ALIASING is what happens to the information you did NOT keep — and it does not vanish, IT FOLDS BACK, AS A BIAS.** Not analogies but restatements: **cell-average ≡ anti-aliased (a box filter); point-sample ≡ aliased** · **the checkerboard/invisible mode ≡ the Nyquist mode ≡ a ZERO in the scheme's transfer function** (Cardiff's "rank deficiency"), which is exactly why **STAGGERING works — it halves the effective derivative spacing and moves the null mode out of range** · **stabilisation ≡ a HIGH-PASS DAMPING FILTER**, so `alpha_stab` is a filter GAIN, not a fudge · **Jensen's inequality ≡ aliasing of nonlinear terms**.
    **AND THE ONE THAT CHANGES WHAT WE BUILD — Mori-Zwanzig / fluctuation-dissipation: DISSIPATION AND FLUCTUATION ARE A PAIR, AND YOU DO NOT GET TO KEEP ONE.** Coarse-graining is irreversible; the coarse system NECESSARILY acquires a memory kernel (dissipation) AND an orthogonal-dynamics term (noise), tied to each other through **the variance you discarded**. ⇒ **Joseph's fated stochastic jitter is not dithering — it is the FLUCTUATION HALF of the pair, and its amplitude is DETERMINED, not chosen.** It stops being a knob and becomes a derived quantity. (Joseph, 2026-07-13, and he is right: *"the non-jittered form is the one making specialized claims that aren't supported"* — uniform is a positive claim of ZERO sub-grid variance, a measure-zero state.) ⇒ **[hypothesis] `water.rs` adds theta-smoothing (dissipation) and NO matching fluctuation, so it should be systematically under-energised at the sub-grid scale — a BIAS. Probe it.**
    **Also settled by it:** LoD is NOT age (coarse is a low-pass filter of the PRESENT, not a memory of the past; LoD couples to timescale only through the dynamic exponent z, and **z is per-PROCESS**, which is exactly why the multirate seam is hard). The honest measure of "age" is **Bennett's LOGICAL DEPTH** — simple to specify, expensive to compute — **which is what AAT's "compute-shortfall" already was**.
  |impact
    `CLAUDE.md` carries the Prime Question + this principle (Level A). `doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md` is the full treatment (Level B before any field-nomos work). TODO gains: **the column-semantics FORK** (point-sample vs cell-average vs band-limited — the code answers three ways today and only the cell-average branch makes volumetric exactness available at all); **four probes** (null-space/eigenvalue, curl-free, well-balanced, fluctuation-dissipation); **the sufficient-statistic contract** (Jensen makes it non-optional); **the multiresolution/wavelet store spike** (mean-pin IS the Haar low-pass with the DETAILS DISCARDED — which is precisely why refluxing is needed; store them and the seam never happens; it may also retire `detail->abstract`); and **two grid leads the report never tested** (staggering — compatible with our quadtree, possibly MANDATORY for ocean/atmosphere; and vertex-centred FV on a triangular mesh, whose dual is hexagonal).
  |ref doc/theory/discretisation-and-information.md · ref/research/pdfs/markdowns/cardiff-2021-thirty/ · CLAUDE.md · TODO.md

|decision[mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  MEASURED (`grid_lab` §9a, commit 193669a). The first application of the bias-vs-noise audit, and it returns a decisive answer: **MFD's error on our cube-sphere is a BIAS, not noise, and it CANNOT BE OUT-RESOLVED.** ⚠ THIS IS A MEASUREMENT, NOT A VERDICT — it does not adjudicate the grid question, which remains Joseph's (`grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated`).
  |reason
    **(1) It does not converge away — and that is a THEOREM, not a trend.** As you refine, a cell's neighbourhood approaches the lattice sheared by the projection's **Jacobian**, whose closed form contains **no N**. So the fan converges to a fixed non-uniform limit. Corner gap error: 14.2° (L5) → 15.0° (L9) → **15.0° (L19) → 15.0° (L23)**, matching the closed form to <1e-4°. **L5→L19 refines cells 16,384× and moves the defect ~1° — in the WRONG direction.** The "it will wash out at the scale erosion actually runs" escape hatch is CLOSED.
    **(2) It is a FIELD over the face, not a number.** Exactly zero at a face CENTRE (MFD is perfectly correct there — it reproduces the perfect-lattice control), rising monotonically outward. Area-weighted over the sphere: **median 6.8°, 90th pct 14.3°, worst 18.5°; only 37.8% of the planet is under 5°.** UNPREDICTED, and it matters: there are **TWO independent defects peaking in DIFFERENT places** — *shear* (120° axes at the face corner, zero at edge-midpoints) and *anisotropy* (√2:1 at the edge-midpoints, 1:1 at the corner). Neither alone explains the field.
    **(3) THE ANSWER TO THE AUDIT: BIAS.** Away from a face centre MFD's eight evenly-spaced attractors **COLLAPSE INTO TWO** (Δrms 16° at the corner; 97% of the compass pushed >1°). On a cone whose exact flow lines are meridians, a plume ends **474 km — 12 cell-widths — off its true meridian.** And refining makes it WORSE: drift 4.00° (L6) → **5.75°** (L9), where pure noise would have FALLEN to 1.4°. **The cube-face u/v axes are ATTRACTORS and the 45° diagonal is a REPELLER.** ⇒ **MFD reintroduces precisely the grid-aligned-channel artifact it was adopted to REMOVE.** With a generic (non-face-centred) pole the drift TRIPLES to 16.9°.
    **(4) A carve only the physical frame could produce.** MFD's weights are NORMALISED, so a uniform rescale of all eight distances **cancels exactly** — the absolute `cell_m` is **INERT for routing**; only the `√2` ratio carries content. (It is emphatically NOT inert in `incise`/`talus`.) What does bite: at a face corner the two diagonals are truly **0.94·cell_m** and **1.63·cell_m**, and MFD calls them **both 1.414**.
    **(5) Supplying true distances is REAL BUT PARTIAL** — drift 5.45° → 4.04°. Cheap, honest, and it does not touch the attractor pair. **A distance fix cannot fix a fan that is not a fan.** Gradient-projected edge flux reaches **1.82°** drift and 5.17% vs MFD's 20.76% catchment error.
    **PROBE DISCIPLINE (the standing guard, honored).** Every number carries a control that could have killed it: the analytic fan is pinned cell-by-cell to the Euler-checked mesh's combinatorial adjacency; the Jacobian closed form is pinned to the code (2e-16); the bias probe runs against a **perfect-lattice control** (reads 0.24° — MFD's own intrinsic error, and the baseline everything else is charged against, so the sphere is not over-charged) AND a 120°-rhombus control that must scream (16.09°); the plume's noise floor is read from the four launches the face's mirror symmetry FORCES to zero (at L9 the signal is 16× the floor). And the one that makes "it does not converge" safe rather than convenient: **in the same runs, the SPREAD does converge away (20.5° → 6.7°)** — so the probe is demonstrably capable of showing a quantity going to zero. It did not have to return this answer.
  |impact
    **It kills one option and promotes another.** Joseph's option "the difference is physically negligible at this scale" is **NOT ADMISSIBLE** — a bias does not become true when you zoom in, and this one grows. His **fated stochastic jitter** option is correspondingly PROMOTED from hack to principled fallback: it is precisely a bias→variance conversion, and variance is what the catchment sum can eat. **What it does NOT do:** it does not price the fix. The corrected scheme's hot-loop cost remains UNBENCHMARKED, and that is still the pivot.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/examples/grid_lab/{fan,flow}.rs · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md §9a · commit 193669a

|decision[column-is-a-control-volume-with-sufficient-statistics] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :status-note The FRAME is settled (Joseph: "it very much lands"). The IMPLEMENTATION is not designed. Do not read this as a spec.
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  A COLUMN IS A CONTROL VOLUME CARRYING, PER QUANTITY, A SUFFICIENT STATISTIC (NOT MERELY A MEAN) PLUS ITS EXACTNESS. It is NOT a point, and it does NOT have a slope. Slope, curvature, smoothness and every vector field are RECONSTRUCTIONS over the dual mesh joining the cell centres — derived, never stored, and the manner of their reconstruction is the SCHEME.
  |reason
    Joseph has been asking for a rigorous definition of a column since the beginning and never got a satisfying answer. It resolves into the classical carve, and two consequences follow that are NOT optional:
    ⚠ **(1) A LIVE CATEGORY ERROR IN THE CODE TODAY (measured 2026-07-12).** A tile is a `Vec<f32>` of "surface elevation", one value per CellId — and the system reads that array with TWO INCOMPATIBLE MEANINGS. The conservation machinery treats it as a **CELL AVERAGE** (`ARCHITECTURE.md`: "mean-pinning a fine erosion tier to its parent is R∘L = id **on the mean**" — mean-pin is only coherent for an area-average). The sampler/renderer treats it as a **POINT SAMPLE** (`voxel.rs` BILINEARLY INTERPOLATES `h_m` — bilinear reconstruction is only coherent for point values on a lattice, since it passes THROUGH them). And the generator declares NEITHER: `gen::initial_topography_m(seed, cell, nyquist_level)` band-limits to the cell's Nyquist, which is a THIRD thing — an anti-aliased point sample, which approximates a cell average for smooth fields but is not one. **Nobody has ever said which it is, and the code assumes all three.** (Whether this also causes the seam ridge is a SEPARATE question and is NOT asserted here — the documented cause of that is missing refluxing.)
    ⚠ **(2) THE MEAN IS NOT A SUFFICIENT STATISTIC FOR A NONLINEAR LAW — JENSEN.** Stream power is E = K·A^m·S^n, nonlinear in slope. A coarse cell containing both a cliff and a flat: carry only the mean slope and you compute f(S̄), but the physics does f(S) averaged. Those are not equal (Jensen), and for n > 1 you SYSTEMATICALLY UNDERESTIMATE erosion — forever, never converging away, COMPOUNDING down the catchment. **So coarse-graining a nonlinear law does not lose precision. IT LIES.** A coarse column must carry enough of the sub-grid DISTRIBUTION (at minimum a variance) for the law to be evaluated honestly at that scale. Joseph's instinct that each point is "a distribution with known ε / confidence bands / its own noise capacity" is therefore not a refinement — it is the MINIMUM HONEST REPRESENTATION. This is the sufficient-statistic contract (DESIGN-REDUX §12; the spike-2 `:statistic`/`:exactness` proposal that was DEFERRED, NOT BUILT). Jensen is why it cannot stay deferred.
  |impact
    OPEN AND UNDESIGNED — this is a frame, not a spec. What it demands: (a) the column DECLARES its semantics per quantity (point-sample vs cell-average vs band-limited) — the current three-way ambiguity is resolved by decision, not by convention; (b) fluxed quantities carry a `:statistic` + `:exactness` contract, and a consumer's needed statistic is matched against a producer's guaranteed statistic as a PRE-RUN graph query (spike 2's proposal, now load-bearing rather than speculative); (c) the coarse-graining operator L is declared per quantity and its Jensen gap is an ACCOUNTED, AUDITED bias — not an unspoken loss. NOTE the temporal half is unaddressed: a coarse cell's value is an average over SPACE **and TIME**, so the sufficient-statistic contract has a time dimension too (doc/theory/multiscale-seams.md).
  |ref doc/ARCHITECTURE.md (R∘L=id "on the mean") · crates/vivarium-core/src/voxel.rs (bilinear) · crates/vivarium-world/src/gen.rs (nyquist_level) · VIVARIA-DECLARATIVE-FRONTIER.md (the deferred statistic contract) · doc/design/DESIGN-REDUX.md SS12

|decision[front-door-docs-swept-to-present-truth] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic process
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  Swept ORIENTATION.md / TODO.md / ASSUMPTIONS.md so the ONBOARDING docs state present truth. The 2026-07-12 session made corrections faster than it swept them: everything landed in DECISIONS, and the docs a fresh agent is TOLD to read still carried the refuted versions. Integration-is-replacement applies to the front door, not just to the ledger.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "the last agents weren't able to update the onboarding/orientation documents — it was the best they could do to barely make sure everything was in DECISIONS and other docs." Found on a full read: (1) ORIENTATION advertised "the declared flux web is CLOSED / unmet flux needs: none" — false since the ordinum wiring, which is the whole point (erosion consumes `emerged land`, unkept, so the audit CONVICTS the world); (2) ORIENTATION's "⛔ Read this before building anything" block and TODO SSPrior v3 both still ordered the next agent to build a two-mode crustal prior as "a HARD COHERENCE REQUIREMENT" — the exact frame Joseph RETRACTED in `water-world-is-the-promise-not-the-bug` ("bimodality is NOT a fix to the prior"); worse, TODO's own OLDER section (Joseph, 2026-07-10) had the correct frame and the newer one overwrote it; (3) "spine" survived in five ORIENTATION sites after the rename was executed in code — the very lesson `initial-topography-rename-executed` recorded; (4) test count stale (81/81; actual 87/87, run).
  |impact
    ORIENTATION: flux-web section rewritten (the ordinum GOVERNS the web and currently convicts this world — that is the machinery working); ⛔ block replaced with the corrected reading + Joseph's un-adjudicated nuance kept visible ("the ordinum does not FORBID early emergence — a mismatch is a SIGN that either the model or the ladder is wrong; the early-continents papers adjudicate"); both standing guards stated (probe-that-cannot-fail; check-the-ladder-not-modern-earth); spine -> initial-topography; crate map + CLI updated; regula references corrected to the collapse. TODO: SSPrior v3 rewritten as the **#1 gap (`emerged-land`)** in the ladder's order; the conformance section rewritten around the regula collapse with the STILL-OWED maturity-report display called out. **NOT swept, needs Joseph:** LEXICON.udon still marks `regula` / `slot` / `permit` `:status settled` though the collapse retired them, and has NO `|term[manifest]` entry although two entries carry `|rel :to manifest` edges — a vocabulary call he owns.
